          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">Europe advocates for Ukraine</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/macron-zelenskiy-handshake-agreement-elysee-palace-paris.png" alt="French President Emmanuel Macron and Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskiy shake hands after signing an agreement at the Elysee Palace in Paris, France" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">French President Emmanuel Macron and Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskiy shake hands after signing an agreement at the Elysee Palace in Paris, France. Credits: Thibault Camus/Pool via REUTERS</p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
         
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">At the 3rd anniversary of Russia's war with Ukraine, European leaders are racing to <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-25-02-2025-h2-2-maintain-alliances-and-support-ukraine?source=website" target="_blank">maintain alliances and support Ukraine</a>. This comes amid Donald Trump's shift in stance, pressuring Kyiv into a peace agreement that aligns with Russian interests. French President Emmanuel Macron met with Trump in Washington on Monday. He warned that letting Putin win would be a "huge strategic mistake." Both leaders expressed that they had hope that peace would be obtained.</p>

          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">At the same time, US Prime Minister Keir Starmer provided British troop deployments as security guarantees. Meanwhile, EU leaders gathered to show support in Kyiv and pushed for a $20.94 Bn military aid package. Trump's rhetoric, portraying US aid to Ukraine as a transactional deal rather than a defense of democracy, has raised European fears of American disengagement. </p>

          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Macron seeks to convince Trump that Europe is ready for defense spending, possibly proposing a 30,000-strong EU-led peacekeeping force. With concerns over NATO's future and potential US troop reductions, European leaders race to establish security strategies independent of Washington. Meanwhile, Zelesnkyy said he would be okay with ending the war if Ukraine had a guaranteed path to NATO membership.</p>
        </mj-text>
