          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">Global conflicts trigger internet shutdowns</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;"><strong>Summary: Reports show that 2024 witnessed the worst internet shutdowns. Conflicts and protests were deemed major causes. </strong></p>

          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Access Now and the #KeepItOn recently released a report stating that 2024 was the worst year for internet shutdowns. At​​ least <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-25-02-2025-h3-3-296-shutdowns-in-54-countries?source=website" target="_blank">296 shutdowns in 54 countries</a> were reported, a 35% increase from 2022. Myanmar now leads, surpassing India, with 85 shutdowns, mainly due to its military regime. This is the first time in six years that India hasn’t topped the list.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Conflict was the main cause, leading to 103 shutdowns in 11 nations. Protests caused 74 shutdowns, exams led to 16, and elections resulted in 12. Seven countries, including France and El Salvador, imposed shutdowns for the first time. Cross-border disruptions rose, impacting 13 countries. Platform blocks reached a record 71, with X facing the most restrictions.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Despite these issues, some progress was made. The African Commission urged states to avoid shutdowns during elections, and world leaders pledged to oppose such actions at the UN Summit of the Future. The report recommended that countries conduct investigations, pursue accountability, and ensure remedy and redress for those harmed.</p>
        </mj-text>
    </mj-section>
