          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">Who is Germany's future chancellor?</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/friedrich-merz-cdu-leader-news-conference-berlin.png" alt="Friedrich Merz, leader of the Christian Democratic Union (CDU), speaks during a news conference at the headquarters of the Christian Democratic Union (CDU) party in Berlin, Germany" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">Friedrich Merz, leader of the Christian Democratic Union (CDU), speaks during a news conference at the headquarters of the Christian Democratic Union (CDU) party in Berlin, Germany. Credits: AP Photo/Martin Meissner</p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Friedrich Merz, leader of Germany's Christian Democratic Union (CDU), won the recent election and <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-25-02-2025-f1-6-might-become-the-next-chancellor?source=website" target="_blank">might become the next chancellor</a>. At 69, he brings a wealth of experience in politics and business. In 1972, Merz joined the CDU's youth wing. He served in the European Parliament from 1989 to 1994 and joined the German Bundestag. In 2000, he became chairman of the CDU/CSU parliamentary group. 
</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Internal party conflicts, especially with Angela Merkel, led him to exit politics in 2002. Afterward, he enjoyed a successful career in the private sector, including chairing BlackRock's German operations. In 2018, he sought to return to politics when Merkel announced her departure, and he became CDU leader in 2022.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Merz is recognized for his conservative views. He promotes economic liberalism, stricter immigration policies, and the integration of migrants. Yet, his ties to the far-right Alternative for Germany (AfD) have sparked controversy. As chancellor, Merz needs to build a stable coalition. He must also manage Germany’s economy and immigration while enhancing the country’s role in the European Union. His leadership could signal a return to traditional conservative policies, economic reform, and European unity.</p>
        </mj-text>
